More than $236 billion in financial aid was distributed to U.S. undergraduate students in the 2023-2024 academic year, according to the College Board’s Trends in College Pricing and Student Aid 2024 report. Of that total, federal student loans accounted for $99.4 billion, while institutional grants from colleges and universities provided $67.2 billion. For the 2025-2026 application cycle, the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) opened on December 1, 2024 — a significant shift from its traditional October 1 launch date, after the U.S. Department of Education’s 2024-2025 “soft launch” caused months of processing delays. The CSS Profile, required by roughly 400 institutions for non-federal aid, opened on October 1, 2024, as scheduled. Understanding these deadlines and the specific requirements of each scholarship type is critical: missing a single cutoff can mean losing access to thousands of dollars in merit-based or need-based funding. This guide breaks down the key 2025 deadlines, how to prioritize applications, and what has changed since last cycle.

## Federal Aid: FAFSA Deadlines for 2025-2026

The **FAFSA** is the single most important financial aid form for U.S. students and eligible non-citizens. For the 2025-2026 academic year, the application opened on **December 1, 2024**, and the federal deadline is **June 30, 2026**. However, state and institutional deadlines are almost always earlier.

Each state sets its own priority deadline for state grant consideration. For example, California’s Cal Grant priority deadline is **March 2, 2025**, while Texas requires FAFSA submission by **January 15, 2025** for the Texas Grant program. The U.S. Department of Education’s 2025-2026 FAFSA form features a streamlined “skip logic” design that automatically adjusts questions based on prior answers, reducing the average completion time to under 30 minutes for returning filers.

### State Priority Deadlines Vary Widely

Many states fund aid on a first-come, first-served basis until money runs out. Illinois, for instance, sets a **priority deadline of February 15, 2025**, for the Monetary Award Program (MAP). New York’s Tuition Assistance Program (TAP) requires FAFSA submission by **May 1, 2025**, but early filing is strongly recommended. Students should check their state’s higher education agency website directly — the Department of Education maintains a state deadline list updated annually in December.

### Institutional FAFSA Deadlines

Colleges often set their own FAFSA deadlines for institutional aid. Many selective private universities require FAFSA by **February 1 or March 1, 2025**. For example, University of Southern California’s priority deadline is **February 10, 2025**, while University of Michigan sets **March 31, 2025**. Filing within the first two weeks of the FAFSA opening gives students the best chance at first-round funding.

## CSS Profile: Key Dates for 2025-2026

The **CSS Profile** is a separate application administered by the College Board, used by approximately 400 colleges and universities to award their own institutional aid. Unlike FAFSA, the CSS Profile is not free — the first submission costs $25, and each additional report costs $16. Fee waivers are available for first-year students from families with adjusted gross income below $100,000.

The CSS Profile for 2025-2026 opened on **October 1, 2024**. Most institutions set early decision deadlines of **November 1 or November 15, 2024**, for CSS Profile submission. Regular decision deadlines typically fall between **January 1 and February 15, 2025**. For example, Harvard College requires the CSS Profile by **February 1, 2025**, while Stanford sets **February 15, 2025**.

### Early Decision vs. Regular Decision Timing

Students applying Early Decision (ED I) must submit the CSS Profile by their ED deadline — often **November 1, 2024** — even if they haven’t yet received a decision. Missing this cutoff can disqualify a student from need-based aid packages tied to that admission round. ED II applicants typically face a **January 1 or January 15, 2025** CSS Profile deadline.

### What the CSS Profile Asks For

The CSS Profile collects more detailed financial data than FAFSA, including home equity, small business assets, and medical expenses. It requires uploading current tax returns and W-2 forms via the College Board’s IDOC service. Students should gather their family’s most recent tax documents before starting — the average completion time is 45–60 minutes.

## Merit-Based Scholarships: Private and Institutional Deadlines

Merit-based scholarships do not require demonstrated financial need and are awarded based on academic achievement, test scores, leadership, or talent. The **National Merit Scholarship Program** — the largest single-source merit competition — uses PSAT/NMSQT scores from October 2024. Finalists are notified in **February 2025**, and winners are announced between **March and June 2025**. Over 7,600 National Merit Scholarships worth approximately $30 million are awarded annually, according to the National Merit Scholarship Corporation.

Many universities offer automatic merit scholarships tied to GPA and test scores. For example, University of Alabama’s **Automatic Merit Scholarship** requires admission application by **January 15, 2025**, and awards range from $6,000 to $28,000 per year. Arizona State University’s **New American University Scholarship** has a priority deadline of **May 1, 2025**, with awards up to $15,500 annually.

### Private Scholarship Deadlines

Private organizations set their own deadlines, often in **January through March 2025** for fall awards. The **Coca-Cola Scholars Program** — awarding $20,000 to 150 students — closed its application on **October 31, 2024**. The **Elks National Foundation Most Valuable Student Scholarship** (up to $50,000) has a deadline of **November 12, 2024**. Students should use scholarship search engines like BigFuture or Fastweb, filtering by deadline month to avoid missing early cutoffs.

### Local and Community-Based Scholarships

Local scholarships often have later deadlines — **March through May 2025** — and lower applicant pools, making them statistically easier to win. The average local scholarship award is $1,500, according to data from Scholarship America. High school guidance counselors and local community foundations are the best sources for these opportunities.

## State-Specific Scholarship Programs to Watch

Several states run large, competitive scholarship programs with fixed 2025 deadlines. **California’s Cal Grant** program awards up to $12,570 per year for tuition at private colleges and requires FAFSA or California Dream Act Application submission by **March 2, 2025**. The program distributed $2.8 billion to over 400,000 students in 2023-2024, per the California Student Aid Commission.

**Texas’s Toward EXcellence, Access and Success (TEXAS) Grant** program requires FAFSA submission by **January 15, 2025**, and enrollment in a public Texas university. Awards cover full tuition and fees for eligible students. **New York’s Excelsior Scholarship** — covering tuition at SUNY and CUNY schools for families earning $125,000 or less — has an application window from **May through July 2025**.

### Washington State College Bound Scholarship

Washington’s **College Bound Scholarship** requires students to sign up in 7th or 8th grade and file FAFSA by **March 1, 2025**. It covers full tuition at public institutions plus $1,000 for books. Over 25,000 students received the scholarship in 2023-2024.

## International Student Scholarships: Deadlines and Eligibility

International students face more limited scholarship options, but several notable programs have 2025 deadlines. The **University of Chicago’s Odyssey Scholarship** covers full tuition for international students with family incomes under $125,000, with a priority deadline of **January 15, 2025**. The **Boston University Trustee Scholarship** — full tuition plus fees — requires an application by **December 1, 2024**.

The **Joint Japan/World Bank Graduate Scholarship Program** funds full tuition and living expenses for students from developing countries, with the 2025 application cycle opening in **January 2025** and closing in **March 2025**. Awards cover up to two years of master’s study at participating universities worldwide.

### Need-Based Aid for Internationals

Only about 60 U.S. colleges offer need-based aid to international students, according to a 2024 survey by the Institute of International Education. Harvard, Yale, Princeton, and MIT are among the few that meet 100% of demonstrated need for admitted internationals. Their deadlines mirror domestic applicants — typically **January 1 to February 15, 2025**.

